<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Camera Setting" class="currentChild" href="Camera_Setting">Camera Setting</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
In graphic arts photography, the percent enlargement or reduction at which the original art or copy is to be photographed. On most <a title="Process Camera" href="Process_Camera">process camera</a>s, enlargement and reduction is effected by moving the <a title="Copyboard" href="Copyboard">copyboard</a> and the <a title="Lens" href="Lens">lens</a> certain predetermined distances from each other, depending upon the amount of the size change desired. Changing the size of the reproduction also necessitates the re-setting of the lens's <a title="F/Number" href="F/Number">f/number</a>, as well as the <a title="Exposure Time" href="Exposure_Time">exposure time</a>. These changes can be handled with differing degrees of automation, depending on the camera. See <a title="Photography: Graphic Arts Photography" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/Photography:_Graphic_Arts_Photography">Photography: Graphic Arts Photography</a>. 
</p>
